  "prompt": "What is the meaning of f(2) in calculus?",
  "response": "In calculus, \\( f(2) \\) typically refers to the value of a function \\( f \\) evaluated at the point \\( x = 2 \\). Here, \\( f \\) is a function that depends on a variable \\( x \\), and \\( f(2) \\) gives you the output of that function when you input \\( 2 \\) for \\( x \\).\n\nFor example, if you have a function defined as \\( f(x) = x^2 + 3 \\), then:\n\n\\[\nf(2) = 2^2 + 3 = 4 + 3 = 7\n\\]\n\nSo, \\( f(2) \\) would be \\( 7 \\) in this case.\n\nIn a broader context, evaluating a function at a specific point like \\( f(2) \\) can be relevant for determining behavior such as limits, continuity, or the value of the function at that particular \\( x \\)-coordinate on its graph.",
